text.tspan: Tufte, Visual Display of Quantitative Information, 2001
Tufte, Visual Display of Quantitative Information, 2001
The world is complex, dynamic, multidimensional; the paper is static,
flat. How are we to represent the rich visual world of experience
A TOOL FOR COMPARATIVE FUNCTIONAL GENOMICS
Use of visual clues: Does the graph use strong and accurate visual clues such as
Salience: Are the important patterns in the presented data emphasised by use of
salient visual features such as color, size, shape or added marks?
Symbol uniqueness: Are the same symbols always used in the same context and
different symbols do not have overlapping meanings?
Grouping: Do related objects, such as data points and labels look alike, are connected
by lines, placed close together or enclosed in a common space?
Use of colors: Are the colors necessary and can not be replaced by positional marks
Color coding: Are the colors used in the presentation discriminable (also for color-
blind and in black&white print) and do not introduce bias or unwanted artifacts?
References to related articles from "Points of View" series by Bang Wong:
Visualization Checklist by Bartosz Telenczuk is licensed under

Typeface: Is the typeface used consistently and does not interfere with reading?
Grouping: Is the grouping principle (see above) correctly applied to figure panels?
Arrangement: Are the figure elements aligned to (possibly implied) guides to
emphasise the flow of arguments and express the figure's underlying meaning?
Use of whitespace: Is the whitespace regular and used effectively as a means to
attract readers' attention and make the non-white content stand out?
Bang Wang, Points of view, Nature Methods, 2010-2011
Bartosz Telenczuk, Let your data SPEAK!, 2011
